    "answer": "I now have a thorough understanding of the codebase and the bug. Here's my analysis:\n\n---\n\n## Problem Analysis\n\nThe **stage board is global** \u2014 there's one `Stages` collection shared across all tasks. When you switch tasks, `SelectTaskAsync` calls `ResetStages()` \u2192 `LoadRunHistoryAsync()`, which replays stored live events through `ApplyStageEventToBoard`.\n\nThe critical line in `ApplyStageEventToBoard` is:\n\n```csharp\nstage.MarkRunning(DateTimeOffset.UtcNow);  // MainWindowViewModel.Helpers.cs, line ~90\n```\n\nThis captures **the current wall-clock time** as the stage start. When replaying a `stage_start` event for a task you're switching back to, `_runningSince` gets set to \"right now\". On the next 1-second `DispatcherTimer` tick, `StageRowViewModel.RefreshElapsed` computes `now - now` \u2248 0s, so the elapsed label resets to \"0s\" and ticks up from zero again.\n\nThe fix: use the actual event timestamp already present in the data (`relayEvent.Timestamp`), which is accurate for both live and replayed events.\n\n---\n\n## Solution Options\n\n### Option 1: Use `relayEvent.Timestamp` instead of `DateTimeOffset.UtcNow`\n\nIn `MainWindowViewModel.Helpers.cs`, change the `stage_start` handler in `ApplyStageEventToBoard` to pass `relayEvent.Timestamp` to `stage.MarkRunning(...)` instead of `DateTimeOffset.UtcNow`.\n\n- **Lowest risk** \u2014 the event timestamp is the semantically correct value (it's when the driver said the stage started).\n- **Minimal change** \u2014 one line, no new fields or data structures.\n- Works correctly for both live events (during execution) and replayed events (when switching tasks).\n- The existing `StageRowViewModel._runningSince` field stores a `DateTimeOffset`, so the types match.\n\n### Option 2: Skip `stage_start` replay on task switch; restore running state from the status record\n\nIn `LoadRunHistoryAsync`, stop replaying live `stage_start` events through `ApplyStageEventToBoard`. Instead, when the status record shows a stage is still \"Running\", set `_runningSince` from the event stream's earliest `stage_start` timestamp for that stage.\n\n- More complex \u2014 requires storing/retrieving the original start time separately.\n- Avoids duplicating status-setting logic between the status-record path and the live-event replay path.\n- Risk of drift if the status record and live events disagree.\n\n### Option 3: Persist running-stage start time in the task metric/status record\n\nAdd a `StartedAt` field to the driver-written status record (e.g., `StageStatusEntry`), and restore `_runningSince` from it rather than from replayed events.\n\n- **Most robust** \u2014 survives full app restarts, not just task switches.\n- Requires changes in both the driver (writing side) and the UI (reading side) \u2014 broader blast radius.\n- Over-engineered for a bug that only manifests during in-session task switching.\n\n---\n\n```json\n{\n  \"summary\": \"When switching tasks, `ApplyStageEventToBoard` replays `stage_start` events and sets `_runningSince` to `DateTimeOffset.UtcNow` instead of the actual event timestamp. This makes the elapsed timer compute `now - now \u2248 0s`, resetting the stage timer to 0. The fix is to use `relayEvent.Timestamp` (which already exists on the event) so the elapsed is computed from the real start time.\",\n  \"options\": [\n    \"Use `relayEvent.Timestamp` instead of `DateTimeOffset.UtcNow` in `ApplyStageEventToBoard` when calling `stage.MarkRunning(...)` (single-line change in MainWindowViewModel.Helpers.cs).\",\n    \"Skip `stage_start` replay during task switch in `LoadRunHistoryAsync` and derive running state + start time from the status record instead of replayed events.\",\n    \"Persist the stage start timestamp in the driver-written status record (`StageStatusEntry`) and restore it from there, surviving both task switches and app restarts.\"\n  ]\n}\n```",
